      Sculptor
   =20
 =20

There are not a lot of hostile takeovers of hedge funds. If you run a hedge=
 fund, generally speaking, nobody is going to=C2=A0replace=C2=A0you as the =
manager of that hedge fund without your permission. Your clients might=C2=
=A0leave, if you underperform or otherwise upset them, but they are not goi=
ng to come to you as a group and say =E2=80=9Cwe got to talking and 51% of =
us agree that we would rather have Boaz Weinstein run this fund.=E2=80=9D Y=
our lieutenants might become dissatisfied with working for you, but general=
ly you control the company and they don=E2=80=99t, so they can=E2=80=99t mo=
unt a coup; their only recourse is to leave and start their own funds.
But that is because the traditional=C2=A0hedge fund=C2=A0management=C2=A0fi=
rm=C2=A0is a=C2=A0private company mostly owned by its founder-boss. You can=
, however, have a hedge-fund firm that is also a public company, with publi=
c shareholders who control a majority of the votes. Then things can get tri=
cky.
Sculptor Capital Management Inc. is a publicly traded hedge-fund=C2=A0firm =
with about $34 billion of  assets under management and an equity market cap=
italization of about $700 million; it runs multistrategy and credit hedge f=
unds and=C2=A0has a collateralized loan obligation business and a real esta=
te private equity business. There is, with Sculptor, a lot going on. Some b=
rief highlights:
=09Daniel Och founded Och-Ziff Capital Management in 1994.=09He=C2=A0took i=
t public in 2007. That is: The=C2=A0management=C2=A0company, the company th=
at runs the hedge funds, went public; it trades on the stock exchange and=
=C2=A0public investors can buy its stock. It=C2=A0makes money by charging m=
anagement and performance fees on the hedge funds it runs, and shareholders=
 are betting on its continued ability to make those fees. (The funds themse=
lves are private.)=09=E2=80=9CIn the late 1990s, [Jimmy] Levin was  working=
 at a summer camp in Wisconsin, teaching Mr. Och=E2=80=99s son how to water=
 ski.=E2=80=9D Then Och hired him to work at Och-Ziff, took him on as a pro=
t=C3=A9g=C3=A9, and promoted him through the ranks until he seemed likely t=
o be Och=E2=80=99s successor.=09There was a big bribery scandal that eventu=
ally led to settlements with the US  Securities and Exchange Commission and=
  Justice Department in 2016.=09Och stepped down in 2019 and the firm  chan=
ged its name to Sculptor. Och remains a big shareholder but is no longer di=
rectly involved in running Sculptor.=09But for somewhat mysterious reasons,=
 Och had  soured on Levin=C2=A0and did=C2=A0not=C2=A0hand the firm over to =
him when he left.=09But in 2020 Sculptor=E2=80=99s board  made Levin chief =
executive officer anyway.=09Since then, Levin has been paid a lot of money,=
 and Och has   groused about it a lot;=C2=A0last year he   sued the firm, s=
aying that Levin has =E2=80=9Cdevoted himself to entrenching his position a=
t the company, shaping the board of directors, and wielding that resulting =
leverage to extract ever-escalating pay packages,=E2=80=9D and that Levin h=
ad gotten paid $145.8 million for 2021, even as investors and shareholders =
have not done that well.=09Last November, Sculptor   settled that lawsuit a=
nd simultaneously=C2=A0announced that it was going to try to sell itself to=
 the highest bidder. Things were kind of too weird and acrimonious for Scul=
ptor to stay public.=09Sculptor talked to about 70 potential buyers and ult=
imately  announced in July that it would sell itself to Rithm Capital Corp.=
, a real-estate investment firm, for $11.15 per share, or about $639 millio=
n total. =E2=80=9CSculptor=E2=80=99s investment and leadership teams will c=
ontinue in their roles,=E2=80=9D and Levin will remain chief investment off=
icer of Sculptor as a subsidiary of Rithm, though his pay will be   capped =
at $30 million a year.

That=E2=80=99s the basic background. And then  this happened:

Boaz Weinstein and several other high-profile investors including William A=
ckman and Marc Lasry have made a rival offer for Sculptor Capital Managemen=
t, a hedge-fund firm that already agreed to sell itself to another investme=
nt firm.
In late July, Sculptor agreed to a sale to real-estate investment firm Rith=
m Capital for about $639 million, or $11.15 in cash per Class A share of Sc=
ulptor, which formerly was known as Och-Ziff Capital Management. The offer =
was an 18% premium to Sculptor=E2=80=99s closing price at the time. Should =
it be completed, the deal would leave Sculptor=E2=80=99s current management=
, led by Chief Executive James Levin, in place.
Weinstein=E2=80=99s group presented an offer for Sculptor that was rejected=
 during the sales process and it subsequently increased its bid to more tha=
n $12 a share, people familiar with the matter said. Sculptor shares closed=
 at $11.20 on Friday. If successful, the group likely would install new man=
agement, the people said.
Weinstein runs Saba Capital Management, while Ackman leads Pershing Square =
Capital Management and Lasry helms Avenue Capital Group, all prominent New =
York hedge-fund firms. Financing for their bid for Sculptor is expected to =
come from their personal money, not their firms=E2=80=99 cash.

If you are the CEO of a hedge fund firm that is publicly traded, then any o=
ther hedge-fund manager =E2=80=94=C2=A0or a bunch of them together =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0can try to buy your firm, get rid of you, and run your hedge fund =
themselves. And, really, why not? One complaint people sometimes have about=
 activist hedge fund managers=C2=A0is that they tell companies what to do b=
ut don=E2=80=99t themselves have deep experience running those companies, b=
ut surely Weinstein and Ackman and Lasry=C2=A0do=C2=A0have lots of experien=
ce running hedge funds.
This morning Sculptor filed the  proxy statement for its proposed deal with=
 Rithm, which  goes through the sale process in exhaustive detail. It also =
 put out a statement about the Weinstein group=E2=80=99s proposal:

We have received an unsolicited proposal from a third party that had partic=
ipated in the strategic alternatives process. This bidder has not demonstra=
ted adequate committed funding for any of its bids.
Though this latest bid=E2=80=99s headline valuation is higher than the Rith=
m transaction, this proposal only includes committed financing for less tha=
n half of the amount required to consummate the transaction and underestima=
tes the amount that would be necessary by several hundred million dollars. =
Accordingly, in light of the foregoing and other issues with the proposal, =
the Special Committee has not determined that the bid is, or is reasonably =
expected to lead to, a Superior Proposal (as defined in the Company=E2=80=
=99s merger agreement with Rithm).

There is more detail in the proxy statement.=C2=A0The=C2=A0=C2=A0proposal w=
ould involve the Weinstein group paying $12.25 per share in cash for Sculpt=
or and selling the CLO business to another asset manager (called =E2=80=9CB=
idder H=E2=80=9D in the proxy and not otherwise identified). The Weinstein =
group gave Sculptor equity commitment letters for $288 million of the rough=
ly $650 million check for the company. The rest=C2=A0would come from Bidder=
 H for the CLO business (about $260 million) and debt financing, and they d=
idn=E2=80=99t submit firm commitments for that money. (The board also says =
that the Weinstein group =E2=80=9Cunderestimated the financing and funding =
that would be necessary to consummate the transactions in the Proposal by a=
pproximately $217 million,=E2=80=9D which is pretty weird on like a $650 mi=
llion deal?)
There is a traditional way to read this story. The traditional story goes l=
ike this:
=09Jimmy Levin, Sculptor=E2=80=99s CEO, would like to continue running his =
hedge fund, and the board, which consists of people who like him, would als=
o like that.=09So the board sold Sculptor to a bidder, Rithm, that was not =
really in the hedge-fund-managing business, and that plans to keep Levin (t=
hough at a reduced salary).=09And it did not really=C2=A0engage with a bidd=
er, Weinstein, who=C2=A0is=C2=A0in the hedge-fund-managing business, and wh=
o would not keep Levin around.=09And then when Weinstein offered a higher p=
rice anyway, Sculptor brushed him off, saying that his deal was too conting=
ent, and refusing to negotiate with him to firm it up.

This is the story told by, for instance, Daniel Och.
  [1]
=C2=A0He  sent the board a letter last week grousing about the transaction,=
 complaining that =E2=80=9Cthe Special Committee failed, and is continuing =
to fail, to run a sale process that is designed to achieve the best result =
for all shareholders,=E2=80=9D and that =E2=80=9Csenior management may have=
 interacted with potential buyers or their representatives to influence the=
 outcome in their favor and to the potential detriment of the Company=E2=80=
=99s shareholders.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
You could tell a nicer version of this story. The nicer version goes like t=
his:
=09Sculptor=E2=80=99s=C2=A0clients=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0the limited partners=
 in its hedge funds, whose money it manages=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0like Jimmy =
Levin. They want to keep their money at Sculptor if he runs it, but not if =
he doesn=E2=80=99t.=09This matters in part because Sculptor wants to do rig=
ht by its clients,
  [2]
 but also because merger deals for hedge-fund managers normally require cli=
ent consents: The buyer of Sculptor is basically buying a fee stream on ten=
s of billions of dollars of assets under management, and if all the clients=
 leave then the buyer gets nothing. And so in  the deal with Rithm there is=
 a condition that at least 85% of clients (by revenues) have to agree to th=
e deal, or else Rithm can get out of it, and any deal with any other buyer =
would presumably also require most of the clients to consent.
  [3]

=09The board figures that if it sells the company to someone who plans to k=
eep Levin, the clients will be happy and consent; if it agrees to sell the =
company to another hedge fund manager=C2=A0without=C2=A0Levin, the clients =
might flee and the deal won=E2=80=99t close, leaving shareholders with noth=
ing.

Sculptor, though, pushes back on both versions of this story, or any versio=
n of the story in which it=C2=A0considered Levin=E2=80=99s interests. In Sc=
ulptor=E2=80=99s telling, in the proxy statement, the special committee was=
 not concerned at all about Jimmy Levin=E2=80=99s continued employment.
  [4]
 When it started discussions with potential buyers, it told management =E2=
=80=9Cthat the Company=E2=80=99s management would not be permitted to engag=
e in any negotiations with any prospective counterparties to a potential tr=
ansaction=E2=80=9D until the special committee had approved a deal, and it =
told bidders =E2=80=9Cthat interested parties would not be required to reta=
in any Company personnel following the closing of the potential transaction=
=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cto refrain from discussions or negotiations with the=
 Company=E2=80=99s management regarding go-forward employment terms and/or =
management rollover=E2=80=9D until they had a deal. And then it tried to ge=
t the highest possible price for public shareholders, which turned out to b=
e $11.15 per share from Rithm.
In Sculptor=E2=80=99s story, the problem is just that the Weinstein group n=
ever made a real bid. Weinstein was=C2=A0part of the auction process, but h=
is bid was lower than Rithm=E2=80=99s ($11 per share) and more contingent. =
Now the group has offered $12.25 per share but have not said where the cash=
 is coming from, their deal is contingent on things like selling the CLO bu=
siness and getting client consents, and they could=C2=A0walk away by paying=
 a $19.6 million breakup fee. The special committee would rather get $11.15=
 per share of fairly certain cash from Rithm than roll the dice on getting =
$12.25 from Weinstein and perhaps having the deal fall apart.
I should say that it is a bit easier to find Sculptor=E2=80=99s side of the=
 story than Weinstein=E2=80=99s. When Sculptor started the process of selli=
ng itself last November, it asked potential bidders to sign nondisclosure a=
greements before receiving confidential information. Many of those NDAs con=
tain standstill agreements in which the bidders promised not to=C2=A0submit=
 offers to buy the company outside of Sculptor=E2=80=99s official process; =
if Sculptor=E2=80=99s board didn=E2=80=99t pick your bid in its auction pro=
cess,=C2=A0then you can=E2=80=99t bid again.
  [5]
 That is  changing a bit:
On August 18, 2023, in connection with the Board of Directors authorizing t=
he filing of the preliminary proxy statement, the Company Board (acting upo=
n the recommendation of the Special Committee) adopted a resolution waiving=
 all existing =E2=80=9Cstandstill=E2=80=9D provisions under confidentiality=
 agreements entered into by the Company in connection with the potential tr=
ansactions in order to permit each counterparty to submit confidential prop=
osals to the Board of Directors or the Special Committee. Such counterparti=
es were informed of such waiver on August 21, 2023.
But potential buyers still can=E2=80=99t go=C2=A0hostile:=C2=A0They can=E2=
=80=99t submit a tender offer for the company, for instance, or even make a=
 public proposal to buy it. They can only submit a confidential proposal to=
 the board, which is why the summary of Weinstein=E2=80=99s proposal comes =
from the board that rejected it and not from him.=C2=A0
I have to say, this all seems very =E2=80=A6=C2=A0solvable? Like:
=09If I were Sculptor=E2=80=99s special committee, and I wanted to maximize=
 the price I got for shareholders, I=E2=80=99d probably want to talk to Wei=
nstein? Like, let him talk to investors to see if they would consent, talk =
directly to Bidder H to firm up the sale of the CLO business, let him fix h=
is math, etc., so that if he really does want to pay $12.25 he can. Instead=
, the board =E2=80=9Cdirected the Company and its Representatives to not en=
gage further with the Consortium with respect to the Proposal,=E2=80=9D whi=
ch seems kind of abrupt.=09If I were Weinstein and friends, and I wanted to=
 buy Sculptor, I=E2=80=99d probably want to address the board=E2=80=99s con=
cerns? The amounts of money involved here are just not, to them, all=C2=A0t=
hat=C2=A0large. This is a club of very wealthy hedge fund managers; surely =
they are good for $650 million.=C2=A0If they need to come up with $650 mill=
ion to pay for Sculptor, and they are pencilling in $260 million of that co=
ming from selling off the CLO business, and Sculptor worries that they won=
=E2=80=99t be able to get that much, the simple answer is for them to give =
Sculptor=C2=A0$650 million of signed equity commitment letters from themsel=
ves, try to sell the CLO business, but be on the hook themselves if they ca=
n=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0

The market is pretty optimistic; at noon today Sculptor=E2=80=99s stock was=
 trading around $11.85, well above the $11.15 Rithm deal price.

