The unstable situation at Goldman Sachs Group Inc., from about 1999 until  =
 maybe 2021, is that its partners thought it was a private partnership run =
for their amusement, while its shareholders thought it was a public corpora=
tion run for their enrichment. This was a productive tension. Goldman=E2=80=
=99s partners arguably worked harder and were more loyal and thought more a=
bout the firm=E2=80=99s long-term interests than managing directors at othe=
r investment banks, because they were partners in firm. And junior people w=
ere motivated by the possibility of partnership to work harder and be more =
loyal too.=C2=A0Having good motivated employees is a good way to make a lot=
 of money and, thus, make the shareholders rich. (Disclosure: I used to wor=
k at Goldman, though I was not motivated enough by the possibility of partn=
ership to stay, or frankly to make a lot of money for shareholders.)
But ultimately the difference between a partnership and a public company is=
 that if the managing partner of a partnership gets great economic results =
but is rude to the other partners, they can fire him, but if the chief exec=
utive officer of a public company gets great results but is rude to the man=
aging directors, they can=E2=80=99t fire him. Only the board can fire him, =
and the board is responsible to the shareholders, and if the shareholders a=
re happy and the managing directors are sad then the CEO stays. If all the =
managing directors quit and are replaced by less talented, less hard-workin=
g and less loyal managing directors, leading to reduced economic profits, t=
hen eventually the board will fire the CEO. But being rude to the MDs is no=
t in itself sufficient grounds for termination. Whereas being rude to the p=
artners of a partnership absolutely is! It=E2=80=99s their company, and sur=
e they are there to get rich, but they are also there to feel important, an=
d if the managing partner is rude to them then he has to go.
Technically=C2=A0the shareholders were always right =E2=80=94=C2=A0technica=
lly=C2=A0Goldman, since it went public in 1999, was a public corporation wi=
th fiduciary duties to its shareholders=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but the technic=
alities aren=E2=80=99t always what matters. If you were the CEO of Goldman-=
as-public-company, but you grew up at Goldman-as-private-partnership, you m=
ight=C2=A0treat=C2=A0the partners as partners in a partnership =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0the way=C2=A0you=C2=A0were treated by the managing partner, when you wer=
e a partner in the=C2=A0partnership =E2=80=94=C2=A0and that might be nice f=
or you socially and might even get good economic results. You might maintai=
n the partnership tradition even if you don=E2=80=99t technially have to.
But eventually the firm will be run by someone who=C2=A0didn=E2=80=99t=C2=
=A0grow up at Goldman as a private partnership, and that time is now, with =
Chief Executive Officer   David Solomon, =E2=80=9Ca rare executive atop Gol=
dman who already had a thriving career before he made his way to the Wall S=
treet giant in 1999.=E2=80=9D We have   talked a   few   times about the di=
minished sense of partnership at modern Goldman but, uh, it keeps coming up=
? Now the  Financial Times reports:

Goldman Sachs chief executive David Solomon is facing an internal backlash =
and negative publicity but has for now retained the backing of the Wall Str=
eet bank=E2=80=99s directors and some of its top shareholders.
Solomon is contending with the most challenging period of his nearly five-y=
ear tenure as CEO, with the past 12 months punctuated by falling profits, s=
agging morale and unflattering press coverage =E2=80=94 including a damagin=
g story this month in New York Magazine that asked if he was =E2=80=9Ctoo b=
ig a jerk=E2=80=9D to run the bank.

But the board of directors still backs him, and:

That patience has found support among some of the bank=E2=80=99s biggest st=
ockholders. =E2=80=9CWhile David may be unpopular [among staff], he=E2=80=
=99s done a solid job as CEO for the shareholders,=E2=80=9D said one top-10=
 shareholder.
The shareholder jokingly compared the employee rebellion to the Sendero Lum=
inoso =E2=80=94 the Maoist guerrilla group that terrorised Peru for decades=
 before fading away =E2=80=94 and predicted it =E2=80=9Cmakes a lot of nois=
e [and] peters out eventually, assuming the bank continues to perform solid=
ly=E2=80=9D.
=E2=80=9CObviously he=E2=80=99s not going to be a jerk to the investors. Th=
ey=E2=80=99ve been much more proactive in talking to investors than in the =
past,=E2=80=9D a second top-10 investor said.

In a partnership, =E2=80=9Cbeing a jerk to the investors=E2=80=9D is the sa=
me as being a jerk to the (senior)=C2=A0employees, because the firm is owne=
d by its partners, and if they don=E2=80=99t like you they can get rid of y=
ou. In a public company, those groups are different.
Anyway Jen Wieczner=E2=80=99s profile of Solomon in New York magazine came =
out while I was on vacation and I am sure you have already read it but if y=
ou haven=E2=80=99t you should, it is amazing. For instance:

