<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The unstable situation at Goldman Sachs Group =
Inc., from about 1999 until <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/32465527.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2Fyd=
GljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDMtMTUvZ29sZG1hbi1zYWNocy1jZW8tZGF2aWQtc29sb21vbi13YW50cy1o=
aXMtYmFua2Vycy1iYWNrLWF0LXRoZS1vZmZpY2U_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDgyMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkY=
mdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwODIxJn=
V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc429e265" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
  maybe 2021</a>, is that its partners thought it was a private partnership=
 run for their amusement, while its shareholders thought it was a public co=
rporation run for their enrichment. This was a productive tension. Goldman=
=E2=80=99s partners arguably worked harder and were more loyal and thought =
more about the firm=E2=80=99s long-term interests than managing directors a=
t other investment banks, because they were partners in firm. And junior pe=
ople were motivated by the possibility of partnership to work harder and be=
 more loyal too.=C2=A0Having good motivated employees is a good way to make=
 a lot of money and, thus, make the shareholders rich. (Disclosure: I used =
to work at Goldman, though I was not motivated enough by the possibility of=
 partnership to stay, or frankly to make a lot of money for shareholders.)<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But ultimately the difference between a partne=
rship and a public company is that if the managing partner of a partnership=
 gets great economic results but is rude to the other partners, they can fi=
re him, but if the chief executive officer of a public company gets great r=
esults but is rude to the managing directors, they can=E2=80=99t fire him. =
Only the board can fire him, and the board is responsible to the shareholde=
rs, and if the shareholders are happy and the managing directors are sad th=
en the CEO stays. If all the managing directors quit and are replaced by le=
ss talented, less hard-working and less loyal managing directors, leading t=
o reduced economic profits, then eventually the board will fire the CEO. Bu=
t being rude to the MDs is not in itself sufficient grounds for termination=
. Whereas being rude to the partners of a partnership absolutely is! It=E2=
=80=99s their company, and sure they are there to get rich, but they are al=
so there to feel important, and if the managing partner is rude to them the=
n he has to go.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>Technically=C2=A0</em>the shareholders wer=
e always right =E2=80=94=C2=A0<em>technically=C2=A0</em>Goldman, since it w=
ent public in 1999, was a public corporation with fiduciary duties to its s=
hareholders=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but the technicalities aren=E2=80=99t alway=
s what matters. If you were the CEO of Goldman-as-public-company, but you g=
rew up at Goldman-as-private-partnership, you might=C2=A0<em>treat=C2=A0</e=
m>the partners as partners in a partnership =E2=80=94=C2=A0the way=C2=A0<em=
>you=C2=A0</em>were treated by the managing partner, when you were a partne=
r in the=C2=A0partnership =E2=80=94=C2=A0and that might be nice for you soc=
ially and might even get good economic results. You might maintain the part=
nership tradition even if you don=E2=80=99t technially have to.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But eventually the firm will be run by someone=
 who=C2=A0<em>didn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>grow up at Goldman as a private part=
nership, and that time is now, with Chief Executive Officer <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32465527.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDMtMTQvZ29sZG1hbi1jZW8tcy15ZWFy=
LW9mLWVtcHR5LW9mZmljZXMtaXNsYW5kLWdldGF3YXlzLWFuZC1zdHJpZmU_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDg=
