<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An important form of financial arbitrage goes =
something like this:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">There are glamorous businesses, but e=
veryone wants to be in those businesses, so it is hard to get rich in them.=
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">There are unglamorous businesses =
that are lucrative, but high-achieving people do not want to be in those bu=
sinesses because they want to be able to tell their friends that they do so=
mething glamorous.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you can=C2=
=A0<em>rebrand=C2=A0</em>an unglamorous business in a glamorous way, you ca=
n both get rich and feel cool telling your friends about it.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so if you graduate from Harvard Business S=
chool and tell your friends =E2=80=9CI am going to run a pest-control compa=
ny,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0they will look at you funny, even if there=E2=80=99s a lo=
t of money in pest control. But if you say =E2=80=9CI am going to start a=
=C2=A0<em>search fund</em>,=E2=80=9D they will be like =E2=80=9Coh cool,=E2=
=80=9D even though =E2=80=9Csearch fund=E2=80=9D is a <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32465527.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21=
iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMjIvdGhlLXNlYy13aWxsLXJlZ3VsYX=
RlLWNsaW1hdGU_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDgyMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1d=
G1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwODIxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0=
dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB50cbe09a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  complex-financial-enginee=
ring euphemism</a> for =E2=80=9Cpest-control company.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Private equity=C2=A0is sort of the industrial-=
scale version of this: Hundreds of top graduates of top colleges and busine=
ss schools take jobs that basically involve acquiring and running unglamoro=
us industrial companies, but they=E2=80=99re not =E2=80=9Cball bearings exe=
cutives,=E2=80=9D they are =E2=80=9Cprivate equity investors,=E2=80=9D so i=
t=E2=80=99s cool. Also very lucrative.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/32465527.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vM=
jAyMy8wOC8xOC9zdHlsZS9zdGFuZGFyZC1pbmR1c3RyaWVzLXZhbml0eS1mYWlyLmh0bWw/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB82ae0a8c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> a funny story</a> about the sons-in=
-law of Samuel Heyman, a famous corporate raider of the 1980s. Being a corp=
orate raider: quite glamorous, also lucrative. But he =E2=80=9Cbought GAF C=
orporation, a manufacturer of roofing materials in New Jersey, and took the=
 company private,=E2=80=9D which meant that he was also kind of in the roof=
ing business. He died in 2009, and =E2=80=9Chis sons-in-law, David Millston=
e and David Winter, who at the time were both 32 and already working for th=
eir father-in-law, took over the roofing company.=E2=80=9D So now they are =
very rich scions of a corporate raider, but also, technically, roofers. But=
 they made the most of it: They renamed the company Standard Industries, ac=
quired other industrial-ish companies, and also =E2=80=9Calso invested in b=
usinesses further afield, like MyForest Foods, which makes plant-based meat=
 alternatives; Saildrone, which operates ocean drones for mapping and data;=
 and the electric carmaker Rivian.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also a lot of media companies: The story is re=
ally about how Standard is an investor in Air Mail, Puck and other media st=
artups, and how =E2=80=9Cseveral former Vanity Fair employees =E2=80=94 wha=
t [Graydon] Carter, in an email, called the VF diaspora =E2=80=94 have gone=
 to work for Standard,=E2=80=9D because it is a surprisingly glamorous roof=
ing company:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Jon Kelly, a founder of Puck and another of Mr=
. Carter=E2=80=99s former assistants, even compared Standard to his former =
employer.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe vibe of the office feels like Van=
ity Fair,=E2=80=9D Mr. Kelly told The New Yorker last year when interviewed=
 about his new media venture. =E2=80=9CPeople are sharp and sophisticated. =
It=E2=80=99s just classy.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 2019, Standard started a webcas=
t speaker series that treated employees in its trucking and roofing subsidi=
aries =E2=80=94 and anyone who wanted to watch online =E2=80=94 to events f=
eaturing =E2=80=9Cinnovators and thought leaders=E2=80=9D in conversation w=
ith Mr. Millstone and Mr. Winter. Participants included the author Jennifer=
 Egan discussing curiosity and fiction and the TV host Seth Meyers musing o=
n fatherhood.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you make enough money from your roofing com=
pany, you can make it a <em>classy sophisticated</em> roofing company.</p>
