<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am late to this, but a whole lot of people s=
ent me <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32465527.26=
1426/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9KYWNrX1JhaW5lcy9zdGF0dXMvMTY4OTcxNDQ1NTcxNj=
Y5MTk3MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1e2f490d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> this post</a> from a g=
uy named Jack Raines in which he detailed his plan to (1) use ChatGPT and a=
 fake profile picture to=C2=A0catfish 30,000 men on Hinge into buying $3,00=
0 Soho House memberships in order to impress fake dates and (2) =E2=80=9Cma=
ke $343,000=E2=80=9D by buying call options on Soho House &amp; Co. ahead o=
f earnings. =E2=80=9CI estimate that I contributed $90,000,000+ to Soho Hou=
se=E2=80=99s top line in Q2,=E2=80=9D he wrote. =E2=80=9COf course, this is=
n=E2=80=99t priced in. How could it be? So I bought $50,000 in call options=
 expiring next week, knowing that they will print money after Soho House=E2=
=80=99s earnings.=E2=80=9D I don=E2=80=99t know why those call options woul=
d make exactly $343,000 in his scenario; I=E2=80=99m just telling you what =
he wrote.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, in the event, <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32465527.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9Bc=
mNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4NDY1MTAvMDAwMDk1MDE3MDIzMDQxNjEwL3NoY28tZXg5OV8x=
Lmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1873b3e9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Soho House=E2=80=99s se=
cond-quarter earnings</a> were pretty good, and the stock was up almost 15%=
 on the day. I have not bothered to figure out what call options he would h=
ave been=C2=A0buying, but if he bought them maybe he made money. Soho House=
=E2=80=99s total membership revenues=C2=A0for the quarter were $89 million,=
 up from $66 million in the same quarter of 2022, and from $83 million in t=
he first quarter of 2023, so he clearly did not contribute $90 million of r=
evenue for the quarter.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">People mostly sent it to me with some version =
of the question =E2=80=9Cis this fraud=E2=80=9D and I don=E2=80=99t know, w=
hatever. Like:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you actually catfished 30,000 men =
into buying Soho House memberships to impress fake dates in order to make m=
oney on call options then you probably did defraud=C2=A0<em>them</em>? I do=
n=E2=80=99t know, not legal advice, but it seems rude.</li>=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">Did you commit insider trading? Market manipulation? M=
y instinct is no =E2=80=94=C2=A0you manipulated <em>economic reality</em>, =
not the market =E2=80=94 but I=E2=80=99m not sure the authorities would agr=
ee. It=E2=80=99s fraud-<em>ish</em>.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px=
;">If you=C2=A0<em>didn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>do this (and he didn=E2=80=99t,=
 come on), is it fraud to (1) buy the call options and (2)=C2=A0<em>post=C2=
=A0</em>that you did it, in order to go viral, make people think you did it=
, and sort of=C2=A0meme the stock up? Sure probably, but honestly that=E2=
=80=99s a better strategy than actually setting up 30,000 fake Hinge dates.=
 Not legal advice!</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mostly though I want to point out that if you =
ever concoct a cunning plan to create $90 million of revenue for a public c=
ompany and cash in by making $343,000 for yourself on short-dated call opti=
on trades, you have made a terrible mistake, even if everything works perfe=
ctly! You=E2=80=99re capturing like 0.4% of the value you created. If you c=
an create $90 million in revenue for Soho House out of nowhere, just call t=
hem up and offer to do it for a 10% cut, which is $9 million, which is so m=
uch more than $343,000. Really though if your plan is to trick people into =
paying $90 million for something that costs you nothing, you should be aimi=
ng to capture $90 million of that! Not legal advice!=C2=A0</p>
